node.text:
An amazing avalanche at Kapuche Glacier Lake, Nepal! 🤯
Watch until the end to see it reach the bottom.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
📍Located at 2546m above sea level, Kapuche Glacier lake is the lowest altitude glacier lake in Nepal.

Video speed x 2.5 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
🎥 by @Naren32

node.text:
Extremely rare light phenomena near the telescopes at Maunakea captured on camera!

A so called 'red sprite' and a 'blue jet' are shooting up from the top of the cloud deck, striking out towards space.

(Credit: International Gemini Observatory/NOIRLab/NSF/AURA/A. Smith)

node.text:
The collision of two galaxies! This beautiful yet violent phenomenon is bigger than humanity's scale and can take up to millions and even billions of years🌌🌌

Did you know?
Our galaxy, The Milky Way, and Andromeda, the nearest galaxy, are getting closer to each other and will collide in around 4.5 billion years🤯😱

node.text:
The maximum number of photographs captured on Solar Eclipse by an individual is 500 and this record was set by Sham Shankar Bhat S N (born on July 29, 1999) of Shimoga, Karnataka, India. He captured the different phases of the sun and the moon and also made a collage of all the photographs on December 26, 2019.

Image credit : @shamshankarbhats

node.text:
Falcon 9 rocket creating an amazing twilight phenomenon in the nightsky! 🚀

A twilight phenomenon is produced when exhaust particles from missile or rocket propellant left in the vapor trail of a launch vehicle condense, freeze and then expand in the less dense upper atmosphere. The exhaust plume, which is suspended against a dark sky, is then illuminated by reflective high-altitude sunlight through dispersion, which produces a spectacular, colorful effect when seen at ground level.

The phenomenon typically occurs with launches that take place either 30 to 60 minutes before sunrise or after sunset when a booster rocket or missile rises out of the darkness and into a sunlit area, relative to an observer's perspective on the ground.

Via @ourthirdimension
